<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,620,1728]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1484,1511]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Comments.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lanes &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2004" box="[633,777,1485,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[633,777,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">A. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the pronotum short, the metapostnotum mostly polished with a row of foveae anteriorly. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lanes &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2004" box="[750,895,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[750,895,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">A. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mandible with four teeth; the notaulus complete; the mesoscutum-mesoscutellar suture straight and shallow; the hypopygium plate long and the cuspis with three apical calli, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[506,599,1593,1619]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goela">
<emphasis box="[506,599,1593,1619]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">A. goela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mandible with three teeth; the notaulus incomplete posteriorly; the mesoscutum-mesoscutellar suture weakly arched and deep; the hypopygium plate short and the cuspis with one apical callus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
